enter gap-3 text-xs text-mist\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"© \\\",2026,\\\" Hotshot Outfitters — Port Hope, Michigan. All rights reserved.\\\"]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"tracking-wide\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"MICHIGAN GUIDED HUNTS · LAKE HURON CHARTER FISHING\\\"}]]}]\\na:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"c\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[null,[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L3\\\",null,{\\\"parallelRouterKey\\\":\\\"children\\\",\\\"error\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"template\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L4\\\",null,{}],\\\"templateStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"templateScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"notFound\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"forbidden\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"unauthorized\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]]}]\\nb:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"c\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[null,[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L3\\\",null,{\\\"parallelRouterKey\\\":\\\"children\\\",\\\"error\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"errorScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"template\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L4\\\",null,{}],\\\"templateStyles\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"templateScripts\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"notFound\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"forbidden\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"unauthorized\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]]}]\\nc:[\\\"\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"c\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$L12\\\",[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",\\\"script-0\\\",{\\\"src\\\":\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\",\\\"async\\\":true,\\\"nonce\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L13\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$14\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"Next.MetadataOutlet\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"$@15\\\"}]}]]}]\\n16:[]\\nd:\\\"$W16\\\"\\ne:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$1\\\",\\\"h\\\",{\\\"children\\\":[null,[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L17\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":\\\"$L18\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"hidden\\\":true,\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L19\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$14\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"Next.Metadata\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"$L1a\\\"}]}]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"next-size-adjust\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"\\\"}]]}]\\n10:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"link\\\",\\\"0\\\",{\\\"rel\\\":\\\"stylesheet\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0npi_rp6qs2dq.css\\\",\\\"precedence\\\":\\\"next\\\",\\\"crossOrigin\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"nonce\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"1b:I[85437,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/04hm9vf8xmubm.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0y-.2i-zv25eo.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0~a.u3-2ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Image\\\"]\\n1c:I[59095,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/04hm9vf8xmubm.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0y-.2i-zv25eo.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0~a.u3-2ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Reveal\\\"]\\n1d:T332b,\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"\\u003ch1\\u003eCoyote and Fox Hunting in Michigan's Thumb — Guided Predator Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\u003c/h1\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003ePredator hunting is a year-round game, and Michigan's Thumb is loaded with both coyotes and red foxes. If you've spent any time on the agricultural land of Huron County — or talked to the farmers who work it — you know the pressure these predators put on livestock, poultry operations, and ground-nesting game birds. Hotshot Outfitters' guided predator hunts are built around 20+ years of reading this specific landscape, knowing where coyotes run and where foxes den, and calling them into range. It's an exciting, challenging form of hunting that doesn't get nearly enough attention.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThis page covers everything you need to know about guided coyote and fox hunting in Michigan.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhy Huron County Is Prime Predator Country\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's Thumb sits at the intersection of exactly the habitat that supports healthy coyote and fox populations year-round: open agricultural fields for hunting, woodlot and drainage cover for denning, and enough farm activity to provide consistent food sources. Coyotes in this region are adaptable, intelligent, and present in numbers that ensure consistent hunting opportunity. Red foxes share much of the same territory, running the same fencerow corridors and field edges.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe Lake Huron shoreline adds marsh and brushy fringe habitat to the mix. Coyotes are comfortable at the water's edge. They follow creek drainages from the interior of the county right to the shoreline, and those linear travel routes become ambush points for hunters who know where to set up.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor the farmers and landowners we work with, predator hunting provides genuine value. Coyotes take lambs, kids (goats), poultry, and — during spring — deer fawns. Red foxes are serious raiders of ground-nesting bird eggs and young birds. Managing predator populations is not just sport; it's practical land stewardship, and it's one of the reasons our guides have maintained the access that makes our hunting possible.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eMichigan Predator Hunting Regulations\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's coyote and fox hunting regulations are among the most permissive of any Michigan game species, reflecting both the abundance of predators and their status as non-migratory mammals.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCoyotes\\u003c/strong\\u003e: In Michigan, coyotes may be taken year-round, 24 hours a day, 7 days a week by licensed hunters. There is no closed season and no bag limit on coyotes. Night hunting for coyotes with artificial light (including thermal and night vision) is legal in Michigan with proper licensing. The 24/7/365 open season makes coyotes the most accessible hunting species in the state.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eRed Fox\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Fox hunting seasons in Michigan are typically set with a fall/winter season framework. Check the current MI DNR regulations for specific open dates, as fox seasons have more defined parameters than coyotes. Typically the season runs from approximately late October through March, but verify current rules at the MI DNR website each year.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eAlways confirm current regulations at the \\u003ca href=\\\"https://www.michigan.gov/dnr\\\"\\u003eMI DNR website\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/strong\\u003e Regulations can change, and the responsibility for hunting legally rests with each hunter.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003ePredator Hunting Techniques: How We Run the Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003ePredator hunting is a thinking person's pursuit. Coyotes learn fast and adapt to hunting pressure. The techniques that work on naive animals in September will fail by November if you don't adjust. Our guides have spent 20+ years calling and hunting predators on this ground, and that experience translates into hunts that put fur in range.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCalling\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Electronic calls and mouth calls are the primary tools. Rabbit distress calls, deer fawn distress calls, and coyote challenge howls are all effective depending on the season and the behavior you're trying to trigger. During late winter, when coyotes are in breeding mode (late January through March), coyote vocalizations — pup distress, female invitation howls — can pull adult males from surprisingly long distances.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFox are typically called on rabbit distress and mouse squeaks. They tend to respond faster and at shorter distances than coyotes, often coming in at a run. If you're targeting fox specifically, faster setups with quicker calling sequences tend to outperform the long, patient sequences that work on wary late-season coyotes.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDecoys\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Motion decoys — a spinning rabbit wing or a small rabbit/squirrel decoy with movement — add visual attraction that keeps animals committed when they might otherwise hang up outside of shooting range. We run motion decoys routinely on our coyote setups.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSetup Location\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Wind is paramount. Predators rely on their nose more than their eyes, and a coyote that winds you before you see it is a coyote you'll never see. Our guides set up downwind of likely approach routes, with the caller positioned away from the shooters so predators are focused on the sound source — not the guns.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eNight Hunting\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Michigan allows coyote hunting at night with artificial light and legal equipment. Night hunting with thermal optics or red/green spotlights has become highly effective for coyotes in agricultural areas. If you're interested in a night predator hunt, ask specifically when you book — we can discuss equipment requirements and availability.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eSeasons and Strategy by Time of Year\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFall (October–November)\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Post-harvest fields with standing corn being picked make for excellent predator hunting. Coyotes work field edges following rodents concentrated by harvest activity. Fox are in peak fall dispersal, covering new territory. Calling success is high before animals have seen much hunting pressure.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eWinter (December–February)\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Cold weather tightens predator movements around food sources. Coyote packs are established and territorial. Snow tracking reveals exactly where animals are running and allows precision stand placement. This is many experienced predator hunters' favorite time of year because the woods are bare, tracks don't lie, and a cold coyote in February that's answering a distress call is a motivated target.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eLate Winter / Breeding Season (Late January–March)\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Coyote breeding behavior makes adult males reckless. Challenge howls and female invitation calls can produce some of the most aggressive responses of the year. This is when big males cover ground quickly and respond to calls that would otherwise be ignored.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSpring and Summer\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Coyote pups are born in spring and the pack dynamic shifts. Distress calls — especially high-pitched pup distress — become effective as adults respond to protect their young. Summer hunting on crop fields is warm and requires different gear, but the access to coyotes is consistent.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eTerrain: What You're Hunting In\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHuron County predator hunting terrain is primarily agricultural with woodlot and drainage features. Key habitat types:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eField edges and fencerows\\u003c/strong\\u003e: The transition between open crop fields and hedgerow cover is prime coyote territory. Animals travel these edges, hunt the field interiors, and bed in the cover. Standing on a field corner with a good wind and a caller can pull coyotes from multiple angles.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCreek and drainage corridors\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Both coyotes and foxes use waterway corridors as travel routes through the agricultural landscape. Setups along these drainages, with the caller placed to intercept animals traveling the corridor, are consistently productive.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eWoodlot interiors and edges\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Larger woodlots hold coyotes year-round, particularly during denning season. Hunting the perimeter of a woodlot you know holds a resident pack, with a calling setup that makes animals step into a field opening, is a classic and effective technique.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eMarsh and shoreline\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Near Lake Huron, cattail marshes and brushy shoreline habitat hold coyotes that hunt the wetland fringe for waterfowl, muskrats, and anything else available. These animals can be difficult to call in open country but respond well to setups that use topography for concealment.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eLicensing and What You Need\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eEvery hunter on a guided predator hunt must hold:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eValid Michigan Hunting License\\u003c/strong\\u003e (base license covers coyotes and foxes as furbearers/predators under Michigan law)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eFor \\u003cstrong\\u003enight hunting\\u003c/strong\\u003e, there may be additional requirements — confirm current rules with MI DNR\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eNon-residents must purchase appropriate non-resident Michigan licenses\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCoyotes do not require a separate stamp or tag in Michigan. Fox may fall under furbearer licensing requirements depending on season and method of take — confirm with MI DNR. Your guide will brief you on what's required for your specific hunt.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat We Supply vs. What You Bring\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eHotshot Outfitters provides:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGuide with 20+ years of Huron County predator hunting experience\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eElectronic caller and decoy setup\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eScouted private land access with established coyote and fox sign\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eStand selection and setup based on conditions that day\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eYou bring:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eValid Michigan hunting license\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eFirearm: centerfire rifle (.22-250, .223, .243 are popular; .17 HMR for fox at closer range), or shotgun with appropriate loads for fox at close range\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCamouflage clothing with good concealment — full camo including face covering\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eShooting rest or bipod (for rifle hunting)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eThermal or night vision if booking a night hunt (discuss equipment at booking)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCold-weather layering — predator hunting involves long stationary waits in Michigan winters\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eFrequently Asked Questions\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Is coyote hunting year-round in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eYes. Michigan allows coyote hunting 24 hours a day, 365 days a year with a valid Michigan hunting license. There is no closed season and no bag limit on coyotes. It is one of the most permissive predator hunting frameworks of any state.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Can I hunt coyotes at night in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eNight hunting for coyotes is legal in Michigan with artificial light. Specific rules about equipment and any applicable permit requirements should be verified with the current MI DNR regulations. We can discuss night hunt options when you book.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What firearms work best for coyote and fox hunting in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor coyotes in open agricultural terrain, centerfire rifles in .223, .22-250, or .243 are popular for the range they provide. For fox, which are typically called in closer, a .22 WMR or shotgun with BB or #4 buck at close range works well. Shotguns with larger shot can work for coyotes at close-calling distances. Your guide can advise based on the specific setup and terrain.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: How long is a typical predator hunting stand?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eA calling stand lasts 20–40 minutes before you either have a result or move on. Predator hunting is a mobile discipline — if a setup doesn't produce in that window, you relocate and try a new spot. A full day of predator hunting might include four to eight stands. This is very different from whitetail hunting where you sit all day.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What's the best calling setup for wary late-season coyotes?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eLate-season coyotes that have been called at are challenging. Longer, more patient setups with soft calling volumes, downwind positioning, and realistic decoy presentations tend to outperform aggressive calling. Your guide will read the conditions and adjust the calling strategy accordingly.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Do I need camo for predator hunting?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eYes. Coyotes and foxes have excellent vision for movement, and while their color discrimination differs from humans, movement and contrast will bust a setup instantly. Full camouflage — including face covering and gloves — is not optional. Stay completely still when an animal is in range.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eBook Your Michigan Predator Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCoyote and fox hunting in Michigan's Thumb is some of the most technically engaging hunting you can do. Hotshot Outfitters has 20+ years of experience reading this specific landscape and calling predators into range. Whether you want a winter coyote hunt in the snow or a night hunt with modern optics, we'll put together a hunt that delivers.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eContact us to check availability and discuss what kind of predator hunt you're after.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePhone:\\u003c/strong\\u003e (989) 551-4551 or (989) 670-4336\\n\\u003cstrong\\u003eAddress:\\u003c/strong\\u003e 6900 Huron City Road, Port Hope, MI 48468\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCoyotes are out there every night. Time to do something about it.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"12:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",null,{\\\"type\\\":\\\"application/ld+json\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"@context\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://schema.org\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"headline\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Coyote \\u0026 Fox Hunting in Michigan | Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"description\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Guided coyote and fox hunting in Michigan's Thumb with Hotshot Outfitters. Year-round predator hunting in Huron County. Calling, night hunting, 20+ yrs experience.\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"image\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/images/michigan-hunting-coyote-fox-predator-michigan-01.webp\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"author\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"publisher\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"mainEntityOfPage\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/hunts/coyote-fox\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"about\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Coyote \\u0026 Fox hunting in Michigan\\\\\\\"}\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"rel